            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Karim Haddad\u2019s story began not in the polished gleam of a Union Square boutique, but in the warm, fragrant air of his father\u2019s Daly City bakery. The only son of Lebanese immigrants, Karim grew up understanding the world through hands-on craftsmanship. He spent his youth watching his father meticulously knead dough and his mother transform bolts of fabric with her sewing machine. Their dedication to a tangible craft was a lesson that sank deeper than any textbook. College was a distant dream that vanished entirely when his father suffered a heart attack during Karim\u2019s senior year. As the eldest, Karim immediately entered the workforce to support his family, his formal education ending with a high school diploma.\n\nHis career started humbly, as a stock associate at a large department store. One day, he was asked to cover a shift at the watch counter. Surrounded by the quiet, intricate mechanics of timepieces, something clicked. The precise engineering and storied history of each brand felt like a modern evolution of the old-world skills he was raised to respect. He devoured every piece of information he could find, quickly becoming the go-to expert. His passion was palpable, and over fifteen years, he methodically worked his way up, moving from mass-market brands to exclusive luxury houses. Landing the manager position at a prestigious watch boutique was his proudest moment\u2014a validation of his self-taught expertise and unwavering work ethic.\n\nNow 37, Karim lives a life of disciplined elegance. His daily routine begins with a Muni ride from his modest apartment in the Inner Richmond, a journey that transports him from the foggy, residential calm to the bustling, high-stakes world of downtown retail. He navigates his day with a quiet confidence, building relationships with collectors who appreciate his deep knowledge and genuine reverence for the craft. His social life is small but solid, consisting of a few close friends from the industry and his younger sister, a tech worker he dotes on.\n\nKarim\u2019s connection to San Francisco is one of contrasts: the working-class immigrant experience that shaped him and the world of extreme luxury he now navigates. He feels at home in both. His aspirations are not of vast wealth, but of ownership. He dreams of one day opening his own small, curated shop for vintage timepieces, a place that honors history and craftsmanship\u2014a tribute to the lessons learned in his father\u2019s bakery, so many years ago."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was eight years old, his hands dusted with flour. His father, in a rare quiet moment, broke off a small piece of dough and placed it in Karim\u2019s palms. \"Gently,\" his father said in Arabic, showing him how to fold, not force. In feeling the warm, living dough respond to his careful touch, Karim understood. It wasn't just bread; it was creation. That single, shared lesson in craft taught him that value lies not in the finished product, but in the patient, skillful hands that shape it.\n\n2.\nHe was seventeen, sitting in the sterile waiting room of Seton Medical Center. The scent of antiseptic had replaced the familiar smell of yeast from the bakery. He watched his mother's hands twist a rosary, her prayers a silent hum. In that moment, the future he\u2019d faintly imagined\u2014college, a different path\u2014evaporated. It wasn't a choice, but a silent vow made in the face of his father's mortality. He would work. The weight of his family\u2019s future settled on his young shoulders, and he stood up taller to bear it.\n\n3.\nIt was a slow Tuesday at the department store. On a whim, he used a small tool to pop open the caseback of a basic Tissot watch. He expected a battery, but instead saw a constellation of tiny, moving gears\u2014a mechanical heartbeat. It was the same meticulous order he\u2019d seen in his father\u2019s kneading and his mother\u2019s sewing, captured in steel and sapphire. That flash of discovery ignited everything. It wasn't just selling an object; it was stewarding a modern, wearable version of the old-world craft he revered.\n\n4.\nA seasoned collector was considering a Jaeger-LeCoultre. The man ignored Karim\u2019s talk of features and asked, sternly, about the Calibre 849\u2019s lineage. Karim didn't flinch, speaking for ten minutes on its history. The man\u2019s expression softened. \"You respect the craft,\" he said, and bought the watch. It wasn\u2019t about the commission. It was the first time someone in that rarified world had seen him not as a salesman from Daly City, but as a peer. That quiet nod of approval was a profound validation.\n\n5.\nFor his sister\u2019s college graduation, he presented her with a vintage, steel Nomos. She, a future software engineer, was puzzled by the manual wind. \"You have to give it life every day,\" he explained, showing her the motion. He watched her connect with the tiny, analog machine\u2014a piece of his world entering hers. In giving her a tangible reminder of history and care in her fast-paced digital life, he felt a success that was deeper and more personal than any sale he had ever made."
